PLUS, the movie is just a movie, the real deal is behind it (if you are not aware of what am I talking about Google "Sony hack" or similar, you can also find a PDF in the official website, if you are interested in.) The content of the movie now doesn¬¥t matter, what does is if it IS realised or banned, the people behind it, and the reactions.
You may think, "Well, but we are talking about a Dictator! He can do whatever he wants to!" Yes, and No. He IS a Dictator, and I am aware of what he and his family did and do to North Korea, but that doesn¬¥t mean he is the king of the world. He can¬¥t just make (for example) South Korea dissapear, becuase there are a LOT (as said before) of different countries out there with power (and no need of a dictatorship).
So, as a "kind of" conclusion: this is pulling a little bit too much (in my opinion) the MORAL situation of North Korea. But FISICALLY, there is a really big chance of nothing happening (which obviously do NOT take out the other chance).

This movie relies entirely on its concept and the whole cancellation thing to succeed. I'm pretty sure even Seth Rogen knew this thing was fucking garbage before it was even released. This is like The Purge, where the concept is interesting and everyone wants to see how they've done it, but the creators already know that that's why everyone is going to see it and figure they don't have the put any effort into it at all because hey, by the time the audience figures it out they'll already have paid for it.

Bland characters, scenes that go nowhere, casual racism, toilet humour, terrible pacing and character development, unrealistic bullshit, and about thirty different occasions where it makes you realise that it actually had potential if even just one person tried to give a shit about making this movie. Title: The Interview Final Trailer - Meet Kim Jong-Un
Comment:
This is a piece of shit movie that makes a comedy out of an evil regime that routinely executes its people for minor crimes, knowingly starves its citizens, and buys luxuries for its elite rather than fixing its economy. It reinforces racist stereotypes of a group people who have no choice in what their leaders do. But people are arguing freedom of speech for a movie that trivializes and makes a joke out of all of that. They are supporting the fact that over and over the media gets to come out with this stuff that makes North Korea the funny joke, that takes away from the reality of the situation because people would rather laugh about fatty Kim Jong Un and nukes and durrhurr than acknowledge that there is a country actively starving and executing its own people and that we do nothing about it. People are ignoring the fact that if any other country had done this about an American president, it would have been labelled propaganda, but because it‚Äôs American-made, it‚Äôs comedy.It breeds a generation of people who think North Korea is a joke rather than an issue.
Seeing it doesn‚Äôt make you a champion of freedom and doesn‚Äôt count as a brave act of defiance against a dictatorship.

Yes, North Korea has long been ruled by an eccentric dynasty of portly dictators with bad haircuts. Yes, the propaganda the regime regularly trumpets to shore up its cult of personality is largely ridiculous. And yes, we on the outside know better, and can take comfort in pointing fingers and chuckling at the regime‚Äôs foibles, but it takes no valor and costs precious little to joke about these things safely oceans away from North Korea‚Äôs reach. When a North Korean inmate in a political prison camp or a closely monitored Pyongyang apparatchik pokes fun at Kim Jong Un and the system he represents‚Äîthat is an act of audacity. It very literally can cost the person‚Äôs life, and those of his or her family members. To pretend that punchlines from afar, even in the face of hollow North Korean threats, are righteous acts is nonsense.

The day will soon come when North Koreans are finally free, and liberated concentration camp survivors will have to learn that the world was more interested in the oddities of the oppressors than the torment of the oppressed.¬†The Interview is a bad movie that trivializes one of the worst ongoing human rights violations on our planet right now, and its distribution, as integral as it is to our First Amendment rights, will change absolutely nothing.

If you read this whole thing and are actually interested in helping the situation in North Korea, you can donate to refugees here: ¬†https://fundraise.libertyinnorthkorea.org/fundraise?fcid=387826¬†

Title: The Interview Final Trailer - Meet Kim Jong-Un
Comment:
I watch fewer than 15 movies a year, always waiting until there is some sort of intelligent consensus that they are good. There is simply too much garbage on the silver screen for me to waste my time on. So "The Interview" would not have been on my radar screen but for North Korea's terrorist threats and Hollywood liberals' being so shameless cowed by those threats.
One more reason to dislike North Korea: it caused me to lose two precious hours on a dump of garbage. It's not funny to have Rogan and Franco sophomorically arguing against each other endlessly about non-issues; it's just annoying.
The only thing approaching anything being funny is the movie routing Rogan to Northeast China through the Southwest of China, with the Guilin landscape in the background. It's the same as routing someone's flight to Boston from China all the way down to the Everglaze of Florida.¬†
The only people approaching anything likeable and believable are, ironically (and they make a big fuss about this word in the movie), Kim (Randall Park) and, much less so, his female media handler, Sook (Diana Bang). And, interestingly, Kim is the only person whose voice is not jarring to the ear.
"The Interview" certainly reinforced my resolution not to waste another minute of my life on a bad movie.¬†
